		{
			"contents": "A major aim of science is to provide data to inform important policy decisions affecting human health and wellbeing. Travel restrictions were at the center of policy debates during the COVID-19 pandemic. While restrictions on movement may limit disease spread, cross-border travel bans have long been controversial (Vanderslott and Marks 2020) over concerns regarding potential economic and social costs, including encouraging xenophobia, as well as limiting the availability of health workers and supplies where needed, and serving as a disincentive for early outbreak reporting (WHO IHR 2005?). The difficulty of these decisions for policy makers were compounded by the lack of data regarding their effectiveness. Nevertheless, in 2020 as new variants of SARS-CoV-2 were raging globally prior to the widespread immunity or availability of vaccines, many countries including the United States, and even local governments such as the state of Hawaii, implemented travel restrictions.  But how effective were they in reducing spread?  \n\nStandard approaches to evaluate the effectiveness of non-pharmaceutical interventions use SEIR epidemiological models to explore changes in the reproductive rate (R0 and Rt) of the virus pre and post intervention (Guo et al., 2022; Lai et al., 2020; Miller et al., 2020; Yang et al., 2020). While these methods are always easier to implement retrospectively when higher quality data are available, SARS-CoV-2 presented additional challenges in that a substantial number of cases are spread by presymptomatic or asymptomatic individuals, rendering key parameters invisible to tabulation. \n",
